# Cursor Instructions — ETL Pipeline

> RoofLink ETL Pipeline — Data Engineering
> Stack: Python, pandas, Jupyter, Google BigQuery

## Project Context
Production ETL pipeline for processing RoofLink CSV exports. Cleans, validates, and loads data into BigQuery.

## Tech Stack Rules
- Python 3.8+ with pandas and NumPy
- Jupyter notebook for interactive mode, `etl_pipeline_logic.py` for library
- BigQuery integration via `google-cloud-bigquery`
- Tests in `tests/` using pytest

## Code Standards
- All data processing in pure functions (input DataFrame → output DataFrame)
- Never modify DataFrames in place — always return new copies
- Every cleaning step logged with before/after row counts
- Sample data must be synthetic — NEVER commit real customer data
- Schema validation before every BigQuery upload

---

## Cardinal Rules

### No Partial Implementations
Never add placeholder implementations, TODO stubs, mock-only features, or partial code that doesn't work end-to-end. Every change must be complete, tested, and production-safe.

- No `// TODO: implement later` stubs that ship
- No fake API calls that return hardcoded data pretending to be real
- No "skeleton" functions that silently do nothing
- No commented-out blocks left as "future work"
- If a feature isn't ready, don't merge it. Period.

### Never Half-Do It
Every PR must leave the codebase in a working state. If you start a feature, finish it or revert. No partial migrations, no half-wired routes, no UI that links to nothing.

### Never Be Unsafe
- NEVER commit secrets, API keys, tokens, or passwords to code
- All secrets go in `.env` files (which are gitignored)
- Use `.env.example` as the template with placeholder values
- Validate all user input — never trust client data
- Use parameterized queries — never concatenate SQL strings

### Always Build and Pass All Tests
- Run the full test suite before every commit
- If tests break, fix them before pushing — never push broken tests
- If adding a feature, add tests for that feature
- CI must pass before merge — no exceptions, no "I'll fix it later"

### Version Discipline
- Follow semantic versioning (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH)
- Every release gets a git tag and GitHub Release
- ROADMAP.md is the source of truth for what each version delivers
- Never skip versions or release out of order
